user
You are reviewing the output of an automated metadata extraction system.

CONTEXT (this is everything you need to know):
- This is an automated extraction pipeline applied to 50 random Digital Object Identifiers (DOIs) sampled from Crossref.
- The pipeline reads publisher landing-page HTML (cached and/or live-fetched) and emits structured metadata.
- No human ground truth exists for these 50 DOIs — this is unseen data.
- The 10 sample rows that follow (via <stdin>) are the first 10 of 50.
- Schema: No, DOI, Link, resolved_links, Authors, Abstract, PDF URL, Status, Has Bot Check, Resolves To PDF, broken_doi, no english.
- "Authors" is a JSON array of {name, rasses, corresponding_author} objects. "rasses" is the affiliation string (yes, the column name is odd; it's the project's convention).
- The boolean flag columns (Has Bot Check, Resolves To PDF, broken_doi, no english) are intended as auditor annotations on extraction conditions, not on content.
- Some cells are empty. Some rows may have all three of Authors/Abstract/PDF URL filled, others may have some empty.

YOUR JOB:
If you were asked to QA this kind of output before it gets used downstream (e.g. fed into a scholarly metadata database), what criteria would YOU use? Propose your own evaluation rubric.

Specifically I want:
1. A numbered list of evaluation criteria (5-15 criteria). Each criterion should be testable against a row of this CSV.
2. For each criterion, one sentence explaining WHY it matters.
3. For each criterion, what severity if it fails — Critical / High / Medium / Low.
4. A short note (~3 sentences) on what aggregate quality threshold you'd require before approving this output for downstream use.

DO NOT propose criteria you can't actually evaluate from the CSV alone (e.g. don't say "verify the abstract is correct" if you have no source of truth — but you CAN say things like "verify the abstract doesn't look like navigation/UI text"). Be concrete and testable.

Respond in markdown. No preamble, just the criteria. The CSV rows follow.
